TY  - JOUR
AU  - Schnitzlein, Charles R.
T1  - Price Formation and Market Quality When the Number and Presence of Insiders Is Unknown
PY  - 2002
Y1  - 2002/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/15.4.1077
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 15
IS  - 4
SP  - 1077
EP  - 1109
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - In most models of market microstructure tractability requires that all market participants know the number (and presence) of competing insiders. I drop this assumption in experimental asset markets. Outcomes are qualitatively consistent with theoretical models when the number of insiders is disclosed prior to trade. When it is not, insiders use the timing and size of trades interactively to hide from the dealers and each other, dealers have difficulty identifying insider trades, and liquidity patterns do not differ as a function of the number of insiders. In general, insider behavior has strategic dimensions not admitted in Kyle (1985) and extensions.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/15.4.1077
ER  - 



